SIMPLE: usage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Usage
<hw>Us"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>usage</ets>,
LL. <ets>usaticum</ets>. See <er>Use</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of using; mode of using or treating;
treatment; conduct with respect to a person or a thing; <as>as, good
<ex>usage</ex>; ill <ex>usage</ex>; hard <ex>usage</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My brother⟦br⟧
Is prisoner to the bishop here, at whose hands⟦br⟧
He hath good <qex>usage</qex> and great liberty.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manners; conduct; behavior.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A gentle nymph was found,⟦br⟧
Hight Astery, excelling all the crew⟦br⟧
In courteous <qex>usage</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Long-continued practice; customary mode of
procedure; custom; habitual use; method.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It has now been, during many years, the grave and decorous⟦br⟧
<qex>usage</qex> of Parliaments to hear, in respectful silence, all
expressions, acceptable or unacceptable, which are uttered from the
throne.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Customary use or employment, as of a word or phrase
in a particular sense or signification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Experience.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In eld [old age] is both wisdom and <qex>usage</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Custom; use; habit.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Usage</er>, <er>Custom</er>. These words, as here compared, agree in
expressing the idea of habitual practice; but a <xex>custom</xex> is not
necessarily a <xex>usage</xex>. A <xex>custom</xex> may belong to many,
or to a single individual. A <xex>usage</xex> properly belongs to the
great body of a people. Hence, we speak of <xex>usage</xex>, not of
<xex>custom</xex>, as the law of language. Again, a <xex>custom</xex> is
merely that which has been <xex>often</xex> repeated, so as to have
become, in a good degree, established. A <xex>usage</xex> must be both
often repeated and of <xex>long standing</xex>. Hence, we speak of a
⟦ldquo⟧hew <xex>custom</xex>,⟦rdquo⟧ but not of a ⟦ldquo⟧new
<xex>usage</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ Thus, also, the ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>customs</xex> of
society⟦rdquo⟧ is not so strong an expression as the
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>usages</xex> of society.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Custom</xex>, a
greater power than nature, seldom fails to make them worship.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Locke.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Of things once received and confirmed by use,
long <xex>usage</xex> is a law sufficient.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Hooker.</au> In
law, the words <xex>usage</xex> and <xex>custom</xex> are often used
interchangeably, but the word <xex>custom</xex> also has a technical and
restricted sense. See <er>Custom</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1588 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Usager</ent>⟦br⟧
